A. Introduction and Motivation

a. Motivation

My initial interest on exploring the relationship between childbirth and women's careers was spurred by my personal experience growing up with my mother who raised two daughters while working full-time. I saw firsthand the challenges and sacrifices that my mother had to make to balance her career and her family responsibilities. Despite her hard work and dedication, she often faced gender disparities in the workplace, such as limited opportunities for promotion. As I grew older and began to learn more about these issues, I became interested in exploring them further and understanding how they affect women more broadly. Women are increasingly entering the workforce and pursuing ambitious career paths, but pregnancy and childbirth can create significant challenges and barriers. Maternity leave, childcare responsibilities, and discrimination in the workplace are just a few of the factors that can make it difficult for women to maintain their careers after having children.

When I was looking for the related literature, I was pleased to find that women's disadvantage in the workplace has attracted more and more attention, and many studies and reports have been published.

b. External Sources

University of Bristol posted an article named "Women ‘less likely to progress at work' than their male counterparts following childbirth" on phys.org. The article highlights the large divergence in career paths between women and men following childbirth. The study, which followed over 3,500 new parents, found that only 27.8% of women were in full-time employment three years after childbirth, compared to 90% of men. The study also found that mothers increasingly withdraw from full-time employment over time and the more children a woman has, the lower the likelihood she will work full-time. (Univeristy of Britol 2019)

Another research conducted by U.S. Census Bureau found that: for women who only have one child, the rate of workforce participation remains at a lower level than before birth, but stabilizes. However, subsequent births decrease workforce participation further. (Sandler et al 2021) With these two external data in mind, I decide to use the data from IPUMS CPS (CURRENT POPULATION SURVEY) to conduct a multifaceted research.

Firstly, we will investigate whether there are significant differences in employment status and earnings between men with kid(s) and women with kid(s). We hope to gain insights into whether women are inherently disadvantaged in the workplace because of gender-based disparities.

Secondly, we will explore whether an increase in the number of children has a negative impact on women's employment and earnings. We aim to assess the impact of childbirth on women's careers. This analysis will provide important insights into the challenges that women face when balancing work and family responsibilities and identify potential ways to support women in maintaining their careers while also raising a family.

Thirdly, we wonder whether the treatment of mothers in the workplace has improved over the past decade in line with the rapid development of society. This conclusion will measure whether our society's well-being towards the disadvantaged group is progressing.

Overall, this project seeks to provide a comprehensive analysis of the impact of childbirth on women's working careers. By examining a variety of variables, we aim to gain a nuanced understanding of the challenges facing women in the workforce and identify strategies to support women in achieving their career goals.

c. Hypotheses

Based on the previous information, I present the following hypotheses.

Description Hypothesis
Null Women with kid(s) have higher unemployment rates and lower incomes than men with kid(s).
Alternative Women with kid(s) have equal or lower unemployment rates and equal or higher incomes than men with kid(s).
Description Hypothesis
Null The more children a woman has, the more likely she is to be unemployed.
Alternative The more children a woman has, the less likely she is to be unemployed.
Description Hypothesis
Null The situation of mothers in workplace in recent years was better than 10 years ago.
Alternative The situation of mothers in workplace in recent years was not better than 10 years ago.

B. The Data Set

i. Dataset Introduction

The dataset I am going to use is extracted from IPUMS CPS. I present the variables, meanings, and codes that used for each variable below. Note that codes in EMPSTAT are preprocessed and treated as groups instead of nunmerical values.

Variables Meaning Codes
Year Survey year YEAR is a 4-digit numeric value.
Age Age AGE is a 2-digit numeric value.
Sex Sex 1-Male; 2-Female
NCHILD Number of own children in household 0 = N.I.U. (Not in Universe; Zero children present); 9 = 9 or more persons (Topcode).
EMPSTAT Employment status 10, 12: Employed; 20, 21, 22: Unemployed
EARNWEEK Weekly earnings Top code: 2885 (Weekly earnings of $2885 or more)

# drop observations with EMPSTAT codes other than 10, 12, 20, 21, and 22
keep_codes = [10, 12, 20, 21, 22]
ipums = ipums[ipums['EMPSTAT'].isin(keep_codes)]

# drop observations with AGE < 16 and 'MARST'
ipums = ipums[(ipums['AGE'] >= 16)].drop('MARST', axis=1)

# recode SEX
sex_dict = {1: 'Male', 2: 'Female'}
ipums['SEX'] = ipums['SEX'].replace(sex_dict)

# recode EARNWEEK (Since 9999.9900 = N.I.U, we will take it as no income for unemployed people)
earnweek_dict = {9999.9900: 0.0000}
ipums['EARNWEEK'] = ipums['EARNWEEK'].replace(earnweek_dict)

# recode EMPSTAT
empstat_dict = {10: 'Employed', 12: 'Employed', 20: 'Unemployed', 21: 'Unemployed', 22: 'Unemployed'}
ipums['EMPSTAT'] = ipums['EMPSTAT'].replace(empstat_dict)
ipums_08_12 = ipums[ipums['YEAR'].isin(range(2008, 2013))]
ipums_18_22 = ipums[ipums['YEAR'].isin(range(2018, 2023))]

I splited the ipums dataset into two separate datasets based on the year range in the YEAR variable: ipums_08_12 and ipums_18_22, in order to make a comparison of the status of women in the workplace between a period of ten years ago and the present, in order to determine whether there have been any improvement in the situation of women in the workforce.

Note:

AGE: We restricted the age of the respondents to be over 16 years old, because the bureau's unemployment rate survey respondents were all over the age of 16.

EMPSTAT: Jobless people are classified into one of two categories by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS)—either unemployed or not in the labor force. To be classified as unemployed in the month they are surveyed, people must be actively looking for work. If they are not actively looking, they are classified as not in the labor force (Bivens 2018). Therefore, for the employment status(EMPSTAT), we consider only those whose employment status is either employed or unemployed, and set NA for those who are not in the labor force and in the armed forces.

# Define a function to create the bar plot
def create_empstat_plot(data):
    data = data[data['NCHILD'] > 0]
    empstat_counts = data.groupby(['SEX', 'EMPSTAT'])['AGE'].count().unstack()
    empstat_counts['Total'] = empstat_counts.sum(axis=1)
    empstat_counts['Employed'] = empstat_counts['Employed'] / empstat_counts['Total'] * 100
    empstat_counts['Unemployed'] = empstat_counts['Unemployed'] / empstat_counts['Total'] * 100
    empstat_counts = empstat_counts[['Employed', 'Unemployed']]
    empstat_counts.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
    plt.title('Distribution of EMPSTAT by SEX')
    plt.xlabel('SEX')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

C. Analysis confidence intervals and testing

Hypothesis 1

Description Hypothesis
Null Women with kid(s) have equal or lower unemployment rates and equal or higher incomes than men with kid(s).
Alternative Women with kid(s) have higher unemployment rates and lower incomes than men with kid(s).

The ttest_ind for Difference in Means¶

$$H_0 : \mu_f- \mu_m = 0$$$$H_a : \mu_f- \mu_m \neq 0$$

Where $\mu$ is the mean of one variable per group

$H_0$ : Women with kids have an equal or lower mean of unemployment rates and equal or higher mean of incomes than men with kid(s).

$H_a$ : Women with kids have a higher mean of unemployment rates and lower mean of incomes than men with kid(s).

We set a 95 percent confidence interval.

In [312]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# filter dataset for people with kids only
ipums_kids = ipums[ipums['NCHILD']>0]

# filter dataset for females and males
ipums_kids_females = ipums_kids[ipums_kids['SEX'] == 'Female']
ipums_kids_males = ipums_kids[ipums_kids['SEX'] == 'Male']

# calculate mean and standard deviation of unemployment rate for females and males
mean_unemp_females = ipums_kids_females['EMPSTAT'].value_counts(normalize=True)['Unemployed']
std_unemp_females = np.std(ipums_kids_females['EMPSTAT'].value_counts(normalize=True)['Unemployed'])
mean_unemp_males = ipums_kids_males['EMPSTAT'].value_counts(normalize=True)['Unemployed']
std_unemp_males = np.std(ipums_kids_males['EMPSTAT'].value_counts(normalize=True)['Unemployed'])

# calculate mean and standard deviation of income for females and males
mean_income_females = ipums_kids_females[ipums_kids_females['EARNWEEK'] != 0]['EARNWEEK'].mean()
std_income_females = np.std(ipums_kids_females[ipums_kids_females['EARNWEEK'] != 0]['EARNWEEK'])
mean_income_males = ipums_kids_males[ipums_kids_males['EARNWEEK'] != 0]['EARNWEEK'].mean()
std_income_males = np.std(ipums_kids_males[ipums_kids_males['EARNWEEK'] != 0]['EARNWEEK'])

# conduct t-test for difference in means for both unemployment rate and income
t_stat_unemp, p_val_unemp = ttest_ind(ipums_kids_females['EMPSTAT'] == 'Unemployed', ipums_kids_males['EMPSTAT'] == 'Unemployed')
t_stat_income, p_val_income = ttest_ind(ipums_kids_females[ipums_kids_females['EARNWEEK'] != 0]['EARNWEEK'], ipums_kids_males[ipums_kids_males['EARNWEEK'] != 0]['EARNWEEK'])

# print the results
print('T-test for differences in means of unemployment rate between women and men with kids:\n T-Statistic:{0:.4f}\n P-Value:{1:.4f}\n'.format(t_stat_unemp, p_val_unemp))
print('T-test for differences in means income between women and men with kids:\n T-Statistic:{0:.4f}\n P-Value:{1:.4f}\n'.format(t_stat_income, p_val_income))

T-test for differences in means of unemployment rate between women and men with kids:
 T-Statistic:39.1986
 P-Value:0.0000

T-test for differences in means income between women and men with kids:
 T-Statistic:-248.0030
 P-Value:0.0000

Analysis: For the T-test for differences in means of unemployment rate between women and men with kids, we have a very large T-statistic value of 39.1986 and a p-value of 0.0000<0.05. Also, for the T-test for differences in means income between women and men with kids, we have a very large negative T-statistic value of -248.0030 and a p-value of 0.0000<0.05. This indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis and suggests that there is a statistically significant difference in the mean unemployment rate and incomes between women and men with kids. The alternative hypothesis, that women with kids have a higher mean of unemployment rates than men with kid(s), is supported.

# Define a function to create the table
def create_empstat_table(data):
    # Filter the data
    data = data[data['NCHILD'] > 0 & (data['SEX'] == 'Female')]
    
    # Calculate the percentage of unemployed by number of children
    data = data.groupby(['NCHILD']).agg({'EMPSTAT': lambda x: (x == 'Unemployed').sum() / len(x)})
    data.reset_index(inplace=True)
    
    # Pivot the data to create a table
    table = pd.pivot_table(data, values='EMPSTAT', index=['NCHILD'], aggfunc='mean')
    table.columns = ['Percentage of Unemployed for Women']
    table.index.name = 'Number of Children'
    display(table)

# Create the table for the ipums dataframe
create_empstat_table(ipums)

Hypothesis 3

Description Hypothesis
Null The situation of mothers in workplace in recent years was better than 10 years ago.
Alternative The situation of mothers in workplace in recent years was not better than 10 years ago.

We are going to measure the situation of mothers in workplace through perspectives of unemployment rate and incomes in order to get a simple and straightforward insight from a large and complicated dataset.

Unemployment Rate: Testing for Differences in Proportions $$H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2 \\ H_1: \mu_1 \neq \mu_2$$

Thus, we can rewrite the hypothesis: $H_0$: The unemployment rate for mothers in year 2018-2022 is equal to the unemployment rate in year 2008-2012.

$H_a$: The unemployment rate for mothers in year 2018-2022 is not equal to the unemployment rate in year 2008-2012.

We set a 95 percent confidence interval.

In [316]:
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# Calculate the sample sizes and number of unemployed
n1 = len(ipums_08_12[(ipums_08_12['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_08_12['SEX'] == 'Female')])
n2 = len(ipums_18_22[(ipums_18_22['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_18_22['SEX'] == 'Female')])
unemployed1 = (ipums_08_12[(ipums_08_12['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_08_12['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EMPSTAT'] == 'Unemployed').sum()
unemployed2 = (ipums_18_22[(ipums_18_22['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_18_22['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EMPSTAT'] == 'Unemployed').sum()

# Calculate the proportions
p1 = unemployed1 / n1
p2 = unemployed2 / n2

# Perform the test of proportions
stat, pval = proportions_ztest(count=[unemployed1, unemployed2], nobs=[n1, n2])

# Print the results
print(f"Proportions: {p1:.3f} vs {p2:.3f}")
print(f"Z-statistic: {stat:.3f}")
print(f"p-value: {pval:.3f}")

Proportions: 0.070 vs 0.040
Z-statistic: 84.189
p-value: 0.000

Analysis: The test results indicate that the sample proportion of unemployed mothers in the years 2018-2022 is 0.070, while the sample proportion of unemployed mothers in the years 2008-2012 is 0.040. The calculated z-statistic is 84.189, and the p-value is 0.000, which is less than the significance level of 0.05. This means that we can reject the null hypothesis that the unemployment rate for mothers in the two time periods is equal. Therefore, we can conclude that there is a statistically significant difference in the unemployment rate for mothers between the years 2018-2022 and the years 2008-2012. The alternative hypothesis (Ha) is supported, indicating that the unemployment rate for mothers in the two time periods is not equal.

Income(Eanrings per week): The ttest_ind for Difference in Means $$H_0 : \mu_f- \mu_m = 0$$ $$H_a : \mu_f- \mu_m \neq 0$$ Where $\mu$ is the mean of one variable per group

$H_0$ : The mean of weekly earnings for mothers in year 2018-2022 is equal to the mean of weekly earnings in year 2008-2012.

$H_a$ : The mean of weekly earnings for mothers in year 2018-2022 is not equal to the mean of weekly earnings in year 2008-2012.

We set a 95 percent confidence interval.

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# Calculate the sample means and standard deviations
mean1 = ipums_08_12[(ipums_08_12['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_08_12['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EARNWEEK'].mean()
mean2 = ipums_18_22[(ipums_18_22['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_18_22['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EARNWEEK'].mean()
std1 = ipums_08_12[(ipums_08_12['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_08_12['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EARNWEEK'].std()
std2 = ipums_18_22[(ipums_18_22['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_18_22['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EARNWEEK'].std()

# Perform the t-test
stat, pval = ttest_ind(ipums_08_12[(ipums_08_12['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_08_12['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EARNWEEK'],
                        ipums_18_22[(ipums_18_22['NCHILD'] > 0) & (ipums_18_22['SEX'] == 'Female')]['EARNWEEK'])

# Print the results
print(f"Means: {mean1:.2f} vs {mean2:.2f}")
print(f"Standard deviations: {std1:.2f} vs {std2:.2f}")
print(f"T-statistic: {stat:.3f}")
print(f"P-value: {pval:.3f}")

Means: 142.58 vs 203.55
Standard deviations: 365.93 vs 496.23
T-statistic: -96.103
P-value: 0.000

Analysis: The test results indicate that the sample mean of weekly earnings for mothers in the years 2008-2012 is 142.58, while the sample mean of weekly earnings for mothers in the years 2018-2022 is 203.55. The standard deviations for the two samples are 365.93 and 496.23, respectively. The calculated t-statistic is -96.103, and the p-value is 0.000, which is less than the significance level of 0.05. This means that we can reject the null hypothesis that the mean of weekly earnings for mothers in the two time periods is equal. Therefore, we can conclude that there is a statistically significant difference in the mean of weekly earnings for mothers between the years 2018-2022 and the years 2008-2012. The alternative hypothesis (Ha) is supported, indicating that the mean of weekly earnings for mothers in the two time periods is not equal. Specifically, the sample mean of weekly earnings for mothers in the years 2008-2012 is significantly lower than the sample mean of weekly earnings for mothers in the years 2018-2022.

D. Conclusion

In conclusion, our project has shown that childbirth has a significant impact on women's working careers, directly affecting their employment status and income. Through our analysis, we were able to demonstrate the statistical significant relationships between variables with several testing techniques, such as testing the difference in proportions and the t-test for difference in means. Despite the progress society has made in improving the treatment of women in the workplace, there are still significant gender disparities between men and women. These disparities are reflected in the data we analyzed, with mothers experiencing higher rates of unemployment and lower earnings compared to fathers in general. Therefore, it is important to continue pushing for progress in closing these gaps and creating more equitable workplaces for women. It is also worth noting the high standard deviation we found when testing our hypotheses. This indicates a large variation in the data set, which can affect the significance of differences in means or proportions. It highlights the importance of considering context and interpreting data with caution, and underscores the need for further research and analysis to better understand the factors influencing these disparities. Overall, our project has shed light on the significant impact childbirth has on women's working careers, and the need for continued efforts to address the gender disparities that persist in the workplace. Through continued research and analysis, we can work towards creating more equitable workplaces for all.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and 
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
